el's Traite des arbres fruitiers, and many others.  The book is divided into sections on fruit-growing in France and Britain, fruit elsewhere in Europe, and fruit in America, as well as citrus fruit, apples and pears, peaches and soft fruit, grapes, melons, and tropical fruit.  Each description gives the background of the book and its relationship to others and is accompanied by illustrations of its contents in color and black and white.  The Pomona includes not only brief bibliographical summaries of each book but also background wssays that place the books in a historical setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFruitvBibliographyvCatalogs. 0aFruit-culturevBibliographyvCatalogs. 0aFruit. 0aRare bookszVirginiazUppervillevBibliographyvCatalogs. 0aRare books. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300242546?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300242546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300242546/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY